    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-05-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-05-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="1138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1138">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.2311/5–2353</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Director, Office of South
                        Asian Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_KDD1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-05-23">May 23,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Dr. <persName>Harry Reed</persName>’s report on his mission to Pakistan to
                        study the wheat problem.</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>The Acting Secretary, General <persName corresp="#p_SGWB1"
                            >Smith</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Drs. <persName>Reed</persName> and <persName>Volk</persName>, members of
                        Special Mission to Pakistan on wheat</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_JJD1">Jernegan</persName>—<gloss
                            target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KDD1">Kennedy</persName>—<gloss target="#t_SOA1"
                            >SOA</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Dr. <persName>Reed</persName> summarized his findings, emphasizing in particular
                    the urgency of aid and the importance of making possible the development of
                    Pakistan’s economy through the use of counterpart funds which would arise out of
                    the grant portion of the assistance.</p>
                <p>The Acting Secretary pointed out the great difficulty which a request for a
                    dollar appropriation would face at this time, to which Dr.
                        <persName>Reed</persName> replied that questions of this kind were really
                    out of his province; he believed the answer would have to be given by
                    responsible officials in Washington. The Acting Secretary said that it would be
                    very unfortunate to provide aid on a basis that would put the World Bank out of
                    the business of making further loans to Pakistan for economic development; a
                    dollar loan would do this. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BML1">Black</persName>,
                    President of the World Bank, had suggested to the President a loan of wheat
                    repayable in kind and the President was very much taken with this idea. There
                    was also the possibility of making a grant of wheat. This could be done <pb
                        facs="0779" n="1829" xml:id="pg_1829"/> without a dollar appropriation at
                    this time through Congressional authorization to the <gloss target="#t_CCC1"
                        >CCC</gloss> to give wheat to Pakistan.</p>
                <p>The Acting Secretary asked that the various alternatives be listed in order that
                    a decision might be reached at Cabinet level on the question of how to extend
                    aid. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_JJD1">Jernegan</persName> said this would be
                    done. The Acting Secretary also suggested that Drs. <persName>Reed</persName>
                    and <persName>Volk</persName> see Secretary of Agriculture <persName
                        corresp="#p_BET1">Benson</persName> before they left town and this was
                    arranged for later in the morning.<note n="1" xml:id="d1138fn1">Memorandum of
                        conversation not printed.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
